  url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0079641708600773},
  urldate = {2026-07-11},
  abstract = {The aim of this chapter is to describe the physical ideas that have been suggested to explain the behavior of helium, which can most easily be related to the properties of the Schriidinger equation. Since the discovery of liquid helium, considerable progress has been made in understanding its behavior from first principles. Some of the properties are more easily understood than others. The most difficult of these concern the resistance to flow above critical velocity. Liquid helium exhibits quantum mechanical properties on a large scale in a manner somewhat differently than do other substances. No other substance remains liquid to a temperature low enough to exhibit the effects. Classically at absolute zero all motion stops, but quantum mechanically this is not so. In fact the most mobile substance known is one at absolute zero, where on the older concepts one should expect hard crystals. Helium stays liquid, as London has shown, because the inter-atomic forces are very weak and the quantum zero point motion is large enough, since the atomic mass is small, to keep it fluid even at absolute zero.},
  file = {/home/soeren/Zotero/storage/ZKJ2RXRV/Feynman - 1955 - Chapter II Application of Quantum Mechanics to Liquid Helium.pdf;/home/soeren/Zotero/storage/P3E2PX8A/S0079641708600773.html}
}

